# Java

Java is the workhorse behind enterprise servers, Android apps, and huge chunks of the internet's backend. It's statically typed, object-oriented, and runs on the **JVM** — "write once, run anywhere." Modern Java even ships a real REPL called `jshell`.

## Your REPL

Click **START** on the REPL device to launch `jshell`. At the `jshell>` prompt, try these in order:

```java
System.out.println("hello, world")
int sq(int x) { return x * x; }
sq(9)
java.util.stream.IntStream.rangeClosed(1, 10).sum()
String greet(String name) { return "Hello, " + name + "!"; }
greet("Java")
```

jshell lets you define methods and evaluate expressions without a full class — great for learning.

## The sample

Open `Hello.java`:

```java
public class Hello {
    static String greet(String name) {
        return "Hello, " + name + "!";
    }
```

Everything lives inside a **class**. `static` methods belong to the class itself. Strings concatenate with `+`.

```java
    static int[] squares(int n) {
        int[] out = new int[n];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            out[i] = i * i;
        }
        return out;
    }
```

`int[]` is a fixed-size array; `new int[n]` allocates it.

```java
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(greet("world"));
        System.out.println("first square: " + squares(5)[1]);
    }
}
```

`main` is the program entry point. Compile and run with `javac Hello.java && java Hello`.

## Try this

1. In jshell, use a stream to build squares: `java.util.stream.IntStream.range(0, 5).map(x -> x * x).boxed().toList()`.
2. Add a `cubes` method to `Hello.java`.
3. Try a `var` local variable in jshell: `var greeting = greet("you");`.

## Going further

The Java Tutorials: https://dev.java/learn/

