# C

C is the bedrock. It sits just above assembly, has a tiny runtime, and gives you direct control over memory. Operating systems, databases, and language interpreters (including Python and Ruby) are written in C. There's no REPL — C is compiled, so you learn by editing and running.

## Your REPL

C is compiled ahead of time, so this space uses **run** mode. Click **RUN** to compile `hello.c` with `cc` and run the resulting program. Edit, RUN, repeat.

## The sample

Open `hello.c`:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
```

`#include` pulls in a header; `stdio.h` gives you `printf`.

```c
void squares(int n) {
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        printf("%d ", i * i);
    }
    printf("\n");
}
```

`void` means the function returns nothing. `printf` uses format specifiers: `%d` for an int, `\n` for a newline.

```c
int main(void) {
    const char *name = "world";
    printf("Hello, %s!\n", name);
    printf("first five squares: ");
    squares(5);
    return 0;
}
```

`char *` is a pointer to characters — how C represents strings. `main` returns `0` to signal success.

## Try this

1. Add a `cubes(int n)` function using `i * i * i` and call it from `main`.
2. Change `%d` to `%3d` to pad each number to three columns.
3. Read a name with `scanf` instead of hardcoding `"world"`.

## Going further

learn-c.org interactive tutorial: https://www.learn-c.org/

