# C++

C++ takes C and adds objects, templates, and the Standard Template Library — all with **zero-cost abstractions**, meaning high-level code that compiles to fast machine code. It powers game engines, browsers, and trading systems. No REPL here; C++ is compiled, so you edit and run.

## Your REPL

C++ is compiled ahead of time, so this space uses **run** mode. Click **RUN** to compile `hello.cpp` with `c++` (C++17) and run the program. Edit, RUN, repeat.

## The sample

Open `hello.cpp`:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <string>
```

These headers give you `std::cout`, `std::vector`, and `std::string`.

```cpp
std::string greet(const std::string& name) {
    return "Hello, " + name + "!";
}
```

`const std::string&` passes the string **by reference** without copying it. `std::string` supports `+` for concatenation.

```cpp
std::vector<int> squares(int n) {
    std::vector<int> out;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        out.push_back(i * i);
    }
    return out;
}
```

`std::vector<int>` is a growable array; `push_back` appends.

```cpp
int main() {
    std::cout << greet("world") << "\n";
    std::cout << "first square: " << squares(5)[1] << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

`std::cout <<` streams values to standard output.

## Try this

1. Use a range-based loop to print every square: `for (int s : squares(5)) std::cout << s << ' ';`.
2. Add a `cubes` function returning a `std::vector<int>`.
3. Replace the manual loop with `std::iota` and `std::transform` from `<numeric>` / `<algorithm>`.

## Going further

learncpp.com tutorials: https://www.learncpp.com/

