# C#

C# ("C sharp") is Microsoft's flagship language: modern, expressive, and strongly typed. It runs on the cross-platform **.NET** runtime and powers web apps (ASP.NET), desktop apps, cloud services, and games via Unity. A standalone C# REPL isn't reliably installed everywhere, so this space builds and runs a small project instead.

## Your REPL

C# needs a project to run, so this space uses **run** mode. Click **RUN** to build and execute the project with `dotnet run`. The first run restores packages and may take a moment. Edit `Program.cs`, RUN again, see the result.

## The sample

Open `Program.cs` (this uses **top-level statements** — no boilerplate `Main` needed):

```csharp
static string Greet(string name) => $"Hello, {name}!";
```

`=>` defines an expression-bodied method. `$"..."` is an interpolated string; `{name}` inserts the value.

```csharp
static int[] Squares(int n)
{
    var out_ = new int[n];
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        out_[i] = i * i;
    }
    return out_;
}
```

`var` infers the type. `new int[n]` allocates an array of `n` ints.

```csharp
Console.WriteLine(Greet("world"));
Console.WriteLine($"first five squares: {string.Join(", ", Squares(5))}");
```

`string.Join` stitches the array into a comma-separated string. `learn.csproj` configures the .NET project.

## Try this

1. Rewrite `Squares` with LINQ: `Enumerable.Range(0, n).Select(i => i * i).ToArray()`.
2. Add a `Cubes` method and print it.
3. Read a name from `Console.ReadLine()` and greet it.

## Going further

Microsoft C# guide: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/

